                <note type="abstract">Goldstein focuses primarily on the Talkhīṣ (Abū ʾl-Faraj Hārūn’s “abridgement” of Yūsuf b. Nūḥ’s Judaeo-Arabic Torah commentary), which, although not containing a separate translation of the biblical text, is replete with glosses and partial translations (from words to clauses), examples of which may be found in the many citations (both text and English translation) supplied by Goldstein throughout her work. See also her specific discussion of the translational element in the Talkhīṣ on pp. 93–100.</note>
